{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472170","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472170"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:55:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:55:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1080"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1080","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1080"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.09,0.16,0.61,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1080"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52066"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1080","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1080"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1080"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37382"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"214"},{"type":"tags","id":"1149"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1225"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14477"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44040"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52066","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52066"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn eight-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parents with a three-week history of painless swelling in the left side of his scrotum. He has no other symptoms. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The right side of the scrotum and its contents feel normal. On the left side, there is a 4 cm soft swelling, and the testis cannot be felt separately. The spermatic cord can be felt clearly.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inguinoscrotal hernia","Testicular neoplasm","Epididymal cyst","Hydrocele","Varicocele"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient most likely has a \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydrocele\u003C/strong\u003E, which is a common cause of painless scrotal swelling in children. A hydrocele is a collection of fluid around the testis within the tunica vaginalis. It can be communicating or non-communicating with the peritoneal cavity. In this case, the patient likely has a non-communicating hydrocele since the spermatic cord is palpable, which is not typically the case in communicating hydroceles. Hydroceles usually present with a painless, soft swelling around the testis and can often be transilluminated. While the diagnosis is typically clinical, ultrasound may be used to confirm uncertain cases. For idiopathic hydroceles in children over one year old, elective surgical repair is the recommended treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Einguinoscrotal hernia\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely in this case. With an inguinoscrotal hernia, the spermatic cord would not be palpable above the swelling, which is not the case here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Etesticular neoplasm\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a firm testicular mass. It is more common in adolescents and young adults, making it an unlikely diagnosis in an 8-year-old child.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eepididymal cyst\u003C/strong\u003E is a swelling specifically around the epididymis, located posterosuperior to the testis. In such cases, the testis can be felt as a distinct entity from the swelling. Here, the swelling cannot be felt separately from the testis, which is characteristic of a hydrocele that envelops the entire testis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaricocele\u003C/strong\u003E is a dilation of the pampiniform plexus in the scrotum. It typically presents as an irregular swelling that feels like a \u0022bag of worms\u0022 on palpation. Varicoceles are more commonly seen in adolescents and adults rather than in young children.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A hydrocele is a common cause of painless scrotal swelling in children.","Non-communicating hydroceles typically present with a painless soft swelling around the testis, with a palpable spermatic cord.","Elective surgical repair is the treatment for idiopathic hydrocele after the age of one year."],"references":["Hoang VT, Van HAT, Hoang TH, et al. A Review of Classification, Diagnosis, and Management of Hydrocele. J Ultrasound Med. 2024;43:599-607. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38010662/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37382"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1080"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37382"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-02T11:13:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-03T21:01:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1080"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52066"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups